{
  "slug": "were-so-back-for-good-backrooms-and-obsession-mania-and-10-m",
  "title": "We’re So Back for Good: ‘Backrooms’ and ‘Obsession’ Mania and 10 Movies We Missed!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2026-06-02",
  "runtimeMin": 120,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda on the weekend 'Backrooms' and 'Obsession' turned into box-office hits, a one-month check-in on their summer prediction game, and quick takes on a dozen releases they skipped while traveling in May.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "We’re So Back: The Box Office",
      "note": "the weekend everyone was talking about",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Backrooms",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Curry Barker's horror hit: $81.4M opening ($36.4M on opening night), A24's biggest ever, past 'Everything Everywhere' in three days. Built on a pre-existing internet fanbase; B-minus CinemaScore, 3.4 on Letterboxd. Works best when it stops trying to be a movie and just 'backrooms.' Kane, 20, is now the youngest person to have a No. 1 film in America."
        },
        {
          "title": "Obsession",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Made for $750,000, now $105M domestic and rising (it went up in both its second and third weekends), the first film outside the Christmas window since 1982's 'E.T.' to do that. A word-of-mouth hit Focus bought out of Toronto for $15M. The Nikki-watching-Bear scene is the part that genuinely unnerved Sean."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Mandalorian and Grogu",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "The heavily marketed Star Wars entry that came in third. Dropped ~70% after two weeks, sitting near $250M and likely to settle $350-400M: evidence, per Sean, that this moment isn't about studio IP."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Summer Movie Preview Game: One Month of Receipts",
      "note": "box-office and Metacritic guesses, checked at the one-month mark; other graded films are reviewed below",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Devil Wears Prada 2",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Guesses of $210M/$184M and 57/68 Metacritic against an actual 63 and ~$209M (still climbing). Amanda's box-office call landed nearly on the money."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hokum",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "$16.8M and a 76 Metacritic. Both hosts were close, Sean a little ahead on points."
        },
        {
          "title": "Is God Is",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "$4.6M and a 77 Metacritic; both overshot the gross."
        },
        {
          "title": "In the Grey",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Guy Ritchie's Jake Gyllenhaal / Henry Cavill film, which neither host had seen. 53 Metacritic, $5.6M, headed to VOD after two weeks in theaters."
        },
        {
          "title": "Passenger",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Horror sleeper that beat both guesses: $15M after two weeks, 41 Metacritic."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "10 Movies We Missed",
      "note": "quick takes on the May releases they skipped while traveling",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Sheep Detectives",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Kyle Balda directs, Craig Mazin writes, from Leonie Swan's cozy-mystery novel 'Three Bags Full': sheep solve their shepherd's murder. Past $100M. 'Babe' meets Agatha Christie: pleasant, remedial as a mystery, and, to Amanda, a touch too pleased with its own meta-ness. Voice cast runs from Hugh Jackman to Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Bryan Cranston, and Patrick Stewart."
        },
        {
          "title": "Pressure",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Anthony Maras's D-Day weather drama: Eisenhower (Brendan Fraser) and meteorologist Captain Stagg (Andrew Scott, playing him as 'British Miranda Priestly') in wood-paneled war rooms yelling about June 5th. Fraser is miscast but the film wins you over; Carrie Condon again as the woman keeping the men okay. A 'napalm ultra of dad movies.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "I Love Boosters",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Boots Riley's first film since 'Sorry to Bother You': professional shoplifters against a fashion mogul (Demi Moore), with Keke Palmer, Naomi Ackie, and LaKeith Stanfield. More invention per frame than anything else this year; both hosts feel the macro doesn't hold. John Carpenter's 'They Live' is the clear influence, with a tune-yards score."
        },
        {
          "title": "Billie Eilish - Hit Me Hard and Soft: The Tour (Live in 3D)",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "A straightforward concert film co-directed with James Cameron. Well shot, with time spent backstage and under the stage, but thin. She already had the definitive doc in R.J. Cutler's 2021 film. Flopped at $9.9M despite her streaming numbers."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Wizard of the Kremlin",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Olivier Assayas adapts the novel: Jude Law as Putin (bad orange wig, frequently shirtless) and Paul Dano as his fictionalized spin doctor. A docudrama, not the thriller Sean wanted, with questionable accents and large blocks of translated exposition. Law is the best thing in it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tom Clancy's Jack Ryan: Ghost War",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "A feature spun off the Krasinski series: Ryan pulled back in for one more job, a Bourne-in-reverse across London, Dubai, and New York. 'The Downton Abbey movie version of Jack Ryan,' with Sienna Miller and Wendell Pierce. Expensive-looking and a little bad."
        },
        {
          "title": "Power Ballad",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "John Carney ('Once'). A washed-up boy-band singer (Nick Jonas) lifts an Irish wedding singer's (Paul Rudd) song and rides it to a comeback. Rudd is winning; the resolution doesn't satisfy. Sold almost entirely by the song."
        },
        {
          "title": "Remarkably Bright Creatures",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Netflix. Sally Field and Lewis Pullman strike up a friendship at an aquarium, narrated by an octopus named Marcellus (Alfred Molina), from the 2022 novel. Sweeter than it needs to be; filed under streaming pablum, though Pullman is charming."
        },
        {
          "title": "Propeller One-Way Night Coach",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Travolta's directorial debut, from his own children's book: 62 minutes on Apple TV+ of a boy riding planes and narrating them, with Travolta reading his own text. Handsome production design; barely a film. Sparks a Travolta Hall of Fame idea for 2029."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mortal Kombat II",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Simon McQuoid returns; Karl Urban as Johnny Cage, thrust into the tournament. A 10 out of 10 whenever the characters kill each other, a 0 whenever anyone speaks. 'Highly recommend it. Also, never watch it.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Lorne",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Morgan Neville's Lorne Michaels documentary, his second on a giant American figure this year. Entertaining and candy-filled, but no closer to the man: the Susan Morrison biography goes deeper. Best bits: Mulaney on why Lorne accepts your material, and the camera trained on Lorne watching sketches."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tuner",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Daniel Roher. A piano tuner whose ear lets him crack safes falls in with a criminal outfit: Leo Woodall, Dustin Hoffman, Havana Rose Liu. Old-fashioned and entertaining; would have been a Woodall breakthrough at a bigger scale."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Breadwinner",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Mandy Moore's May release. Name-checked at the close; neither host got to it."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
